# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: crispr-cas9-deep
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] The Cas9 endonuclease introduces site-specific double-stranded breaks in DNA, enabling gene inactivation, removal, or insertion through cellular repair mechanisms such as non-homologous end joining or homologous recombination.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] Cas9 was discovered in *S. pyogenes* and later in *S. thermophilus.* It functions with two small RNAs—crRNA and tracrRNA—to form a four-component complex.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] In 2012, Doudna and Charpentier fused the RNAs into a single-guide RNA, enabling Cas9 to cut specific DNA sequences.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] These developments spurred genome modification efforts, including groups led by Zhang and Church who showed genome editing in human cells.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] Variants of Cas9, including Cas9 nickase (Cas9n), that create single-strand breaks, and versions recognizing different PAM sequences, address specific Cas9 limitations.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] CRISPR-Cas9 technology has raised ethical and regulatory concerns, particularly regarding human germline editing and genetic enhancement.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] The CRISPR/Cas system evolved in nature as a means for bacteria to protect themselves from invading viruses and bacteriophages by inserting pieces of their DNA into the host genome.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] This allowed the adaptive immune system to respond accordingly on a subsequent infection.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] It was discovered in *Streptococcus pyogenes* and later found across many other species.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] Cas9 was first identified in *Streptococcus pyogenes* as a CRISPR-associated protein, originally referred to as Cas5, involved in the bacterial adaptive immune system.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] Studies found Cas9 contains a nuclease domain, the effector enzyme responsible for generating double-stranded DNA breaks in the type II CRISPR system.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] Researchers identified that Cas9 activity depends on two RNA molecules: CRISPR RNA (crRNA), which guides the enzyme to target DNA sequences, and trans-activating CRISPR RNA (tracrRNA), which is required for nuclease activity.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] In 2012, Jennifer Doudna and Emmanuelle Charpentier re-engineered the Cas9 endonuclease into a simplified two-component system by fusing the two RNA molecules into a single-guide RNA that, when combined with Cas9, could find and cut the DNA target specified by the guide RNA.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] That same year, research showed that CRISPR Cas9 components could be programmed for site-specific double stranded DNA breaks in vitro, laying the foundation for genome editing.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] By manipulating the nucleotide sequence of the guide RNA, the artificial Cas9 system could be programmed to target and cleave DNA sequence for separation.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] Around the same time, a collaboration including Virginijus Šikšnys, Gasiūnas, Barrangou, and Horvath showed that Cas9 from the *S. thermophilus* CRISPR system can also be reprogrammed by modifying its crRNA sequence to target specific DNA sites.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] In 2013, research groups led by Feng Zhang and George Church reported successful targeted DNA editing in human genomes, marking the first use of CRISPR-Cas9 for targeted modification in eukaryotic systems.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] These findings advanced the development of CRISPR-Cas9 as a versatile genome editing tool across a wide range of organisms.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] Beyond DNA cleavage, CRISPR Cas9 has been modified to function as programmable transcription factors that allow activation or silencing of targeted genes.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] The significance of the system's development was formally recognized in 2020, when Emmanuelle Charpentier and Jennifer Doudna were awarded a Nobel Prize in Chemistry for their work in CRISPR Cas9 genome editing.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] Native Cas9 is a 160-kilodalton endonuclease that requires a guide RNA composed of two distinct RNA molecules: CRISPR RNA (crRNA) and trans-activating crRNA (tracrRNA).
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] In 2013, Mali, et al. and Gilbert, et al. reported that non-cleaving Cas9 variants can control transcriptional activators or repressors at specific DNA sequences.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] In the same year, Bikard, et al. reported that dCas9 can block RNA polymerase at promoters or during elongation, silencing genes.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] In 2014, Esvelt, Smidler, Catteruccia, and Church suggested that Cas9-based gene drives could spread genetic modifications through entire organism populations.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] In 2017, Li, et al. reported that Cas9 can target the end of the Hepatitis B viral genome ends, reducing infection.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] Jensen et al., reported that dCas9 alters chromatin structure when fused to chromatin remodelers, .
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] O’Geen, et al., reported that dCas9 with FOG1 represses genes by methylating H3K27.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] Lowder, et al., reported that dCas9 represses plant genes like *AtCSTF64* when fused to repressor domains.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] In 2018, Lee, et al., reported that engineered Cas9 reduces off-target effects by altering reaction rates.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] In 2019, Chen and Page-McCaw reported that Cas9 suppresses HIV-1 long terminal repeats, mutating the viral genome.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] In 2020, Uddin, Rudin, and Sen reported that Cas9 variants, such as Cas9 nickase, improve genome editing by reducing off-target effects.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] In 2025, Zhou, Diao, Li, and colleagues reported that **apoNmeCas9** (an RNA-free form of NmeCas9) can stimulate Cas1–Cas2-mediated CRISPR spacer acquisition in a type II-C system when CRISPR RNA levels are low.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] CRISPR systems in bacteria and archaea function as programmable restriction enzymes to combat viruses and plasmids.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] CRISPR loci consist of short, palindromic repeats and variable spacers (24–48 nucleotides) that store sequences from foreign DNA.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] Adjacent cas genes, including universal cas1 and cas2, and type II-specific cas9, encode proteins for immunity.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] Cas9 uses crRNA and tracrRNA to form a complex that targets and cleaves foreign DNA matching the spacer sequence.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] During the adaptation stage, CRISPR systems integrate spacers from viral"protospacers” into the CRISPR locus.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] It requiring the presence of a PAM, such as NGG in *S.pyogenes*) for recognition.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] Cas9 ensures functional spacer acquisition.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] However, spacers can be lost via homologous recombination.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] The nuclease lobe alone is sufficient to stimulate acquisition, whereas crRNA-dependent regulation required full-length Cas9.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] This activity is evolutionarily conserved across several type II-C Cas9 orthologues.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] RNA polymerase transcribes the CRISPR locus into pre-crRNA, which is processed by specific endoribonucleases into mature crRNAs, each containing one spacer and a partial repeat.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] In the interference stage, the crRNA guides Cas9 together with tracrRNA to complementary foreing DNA sequences.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] If the targer sequence matches the spacer and a PAM is present, Cas9 introduces double-stranded breaks in DNA, stoping viral replication.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] Inactive Cas9 (dCas9), lacking endonuclease activity, can bind DNA and regulate transcription.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] In eukaryotic cells, dCas9 targets enhancer sequences to prevent transcription factor binding and gene expression.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] Genome-wide screens using dCas9-based repression have been conducted to systematically identify gene funciton.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] In addition to DNA targeting, Cas9 has been shown to cleave mRNA when hybridized with complementary single-stranded containing a PAM complement.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] When fused to transcription activators, dCas9 can be used to activate genes(CRISPRa).
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] Cas9 has a bi-lobed structure with an alpha-helical lobe (REC) and a nuclease lobe (NUC) containing HNH and RuvC domains, connected by a bridge helix.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] The nuclease lobe contains HNH domains which cleaves target DNA strands, and RuvC which cleaves the non-target strand.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] The PAM-interacting domain recognizes the NGG PAM sequence.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] The single-guide RNA (sgRNA), replaces the crRNA-tracrRNA complex, and forms a T-shaped structure with the target DNA.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] A 2014 study reported that REC1 and bridge helix domains are critical for sgRNA recognition.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] Bacterial restriction-modification systems can degrade foreign DNA introduced into the cell.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] These systems recognize specific DNA sequences and cleave foreign DNA, including Cas9-introduced genes, hindering genome editing.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] CRISPR/Cas9 can help with bacterial defense against invaders such as bacteriophages, plasmids, and DNA viruses.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] Cas9, guided by RNA, acts as an endonuclease enzyme, targeting and cleaving foreign DNA.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] It unwinds foreign DNA and cleaves matching sites, similar to the RNA interference mechanism in eukaryotes.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] Other versions of Cas9 can bind but not cleave DNA.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] They can be used to control transcriptional activator or repressor genes and manage gene activation and repression.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] More technically, Cas9 is a RNA-guided DNA endonuclease enzyme associated with the Clustered Regularly Interspaced Short Palindromic Repeats (CRISPR) adaptive immune system in *Streptococcus pyogenes*.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] *S. pyogenes* utilizes CRISPR to memorize and Cas9 to later interrogate and cleave foreign DNA, such as invading bacteriophage DNA or plasmid DNA.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] Cas9 performs this interrogation by unwinding foreign DNA and checking for sites complementary to the 20 nucleotide spacer region of the guide RNA (gRNA).
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] If the DNA substrate is complementary to the guide RNA, Cas9 cleaves the invading DNA.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] In this sense, the CRISPR-Cas9 mechanism parallels the RNA interference (RNAi) mechanism in eukaryotes.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] Apart from its original function in bacterial immunity, Cas9 has been utilized as a genome engineering tool to induce site-directed double-strand breaks in DNA.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] These breaks can lead to gene inactivation or the introduction of heterologous genes through non-homologous end joining and homologous recombination respectively in model organisms.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] Research on cas9 variants has been a promising way of overcoming the limitation of the CRISPR-Cas9 genome editing.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] Examples include Cas9 nickase (Cas9n), a variant that induces single-stranded breaks (SSBs) or variants recognizing different PAM sequences.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] Alongside zinc finger nucleases and transcription activator-like effector nuclease (TALEN) proteins, Cas9 is becoming a prominent tool in the field of genome editing.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] Cas9 has gained traction in recent years because it can cleave nearly any sequence complementary to the guide RNA.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] Because the target specificity of Cas9 stems from the guide RNA:DNA complementarity and not modifications to the protein itself (like TALENs and zinc fingers), engineering Cas9 to target new DNA is straightforward.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] Cas9 targeting has been simplified through the engineering of a chimeric single guide RNA (chiRNA).
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] Scientists have suggested that Cas9-based gene drives may be capable of editing the genomes of entire populations of organisms.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] In 2015, Cas9 was used to modify the genome of human embryos for the first time.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] To survive in a variety of challenging, inhospitable habitats that are filled with bacteriophages, bacteria and archaea have evolved methods to evade and fend off predatory viruses.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] This includes the CRISPR system of adaptive immunity.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] In practice, CRISPR/Cas systems act as self-programmable restriction enzymes.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] CRISPR loci are composed of short, palindromic repeats that occur at regular intervals composed of alternate CRISPR repeats and variable CRISPR spacers between 24 and 48 nucleotides long.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] These CRISPR loci are usually accompanied by adjacent CRISPR-associated (cas) genes.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] In 2005, it was discovered by three separate groups that the spacer regions were homologous to foreign DNA elements, including plasmids and viruses.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] These reports provided the first biological evidence that CRISPRs might function as an immune system.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] Cas9 has been used often as a genome-editing tool.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] Cas9 has been used in recent developments in preventing viruses from manipulating hosts' DNA.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] Since the CRISPR-Cas9 was developed from bacterial genome systems, it can be used to target the genetic material in viruses.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] The use of the enzyme Cas9 can be a solution to many viral infections.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] Cas9 possesses the ability to target specific viruses by the targeting of specific strands of the viral genetic information.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] More specifically the Cas9 enzyme targets certain sections of the viral genome that prevents the virus from carrying out its normal function.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] Cas9 has also been used to disrupt the detrimental strand of DNA and RNA that cause diseases and mutated strands of DNA.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] Cas9 has already showed promise in disrupting the effects of HIV-1.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] Cas9 has been shown to suppress the expression of the long terminal repeats in HIV-1.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] When introduced into the HIV-1 genome Cas9 has shown the ability to mutate strands of HIV-1.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] Cas9 has also been used in the treatment of Hepatitis B through targeting of the ends of certain of long terminal repeats in the Hepatitis B viral genome.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] Cas9 has been used to repair the mutations causing cataracts in mice.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] CRISPR-Cas systems are divided into three major types (type I, type II, and type III) and twelve subtypes, which are based on their genetic content and structural differences.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] However, the core defining features of all CRISPR-Cas systems are the cas genes and their proteins: cas1 and cas2 are universal across types and subtypes, while cas3, cas9, and cas10 are signature genes for type I, type II, and type III, respectively.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] Adaptation involves recognition and integration of spacers between two adjacent repeats in the CRISPR locus.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] The "Protospacer" refers to the sequence on the viral genome that corresponds to the spacer.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] A short stretch of conserved nucleotides exists proximal to the protospacer, which is called the protospacer adjacent motif (PAM).
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] The PAM is a recognition motif that is used to acquire the DNA fragment.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] In type II, Cas9 recognizes the PAM during adaptation in order to ensure the acquisition of functional spacers.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] Loss of spacers and even groups of several have also been observed by Aranaz et al.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] This probably occurs through homologous recombination of the between-repeat material.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] CRISPR expression includes the transcription of a primary transcript called a CRISPR RNA (pre-crRNA), which is transcribed from the CRISPR locus by RNA polymerase.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] Specific endoribonucleases then cleave the pre-crRNAs into small CRISPR RNAs (crRNAs).
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] Interference involves the crRNAs within a multi-protein complex called CASCADE, which can recognize and specifically base-pair with regions of inserting complementary foreign DNA.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] The crRNA-foreign nucleic acid complex is then cleaved, however if there are mismatches between the spacer and the target DNA, or if there are mutations in the PAM, then cleavage will not be initiated.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] In the latter scenario, the foreign DNA is not targeted for attack by the cell, thus the replication of the virus proceeds and the host is not immune to viral infection.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] The interference stage can be mechanistically and temporally distinct from CRISPR acquisition and expression, yet for complete function as a defense system, all three phases must be functional.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] Protospacers and protospacer-associated motifs (shown in red) are acquired at the "leader" end of a CRISPR array in the host DNA.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] The CRISPR array is composed of spacer sequences (shown in colored boxes) flanked by repeats (black diamonds).
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] This process requires Cas1 and Cas2 (and Cas9 in type II), which are encoded in the cas locus, which are usually located near the CRISPR array.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] Pre-crRNA is transcribed starting at the leader region by the host RNA polymerase and then cleaved by Cas proteins into smaller crRNAs containing a single spacer and a partial repeat (shown as hairpin structure with colored spacers).
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] Stage 3: CRISPR interference. crRNA with a spacer that has strong complementarity to the incoming foreign DNA begins a cleavage event (depicted with scissors), which requires Cas proteins.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] DNA cleavage interferes with viral replication and provides immunity to the host.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] The interference stage can be functionally and temporarily distinct from CRISPR acquisition and expression (depicted by white line dividing the cell).
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] dCas9, also referred to as endonuclease deficient Cas9 can be utilized to edit gene expression when applied to the transcription binding site of the desired section of a gene.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] The optimal function of dCas9 is attributed to its mode of action.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] Gene expression is inhibited when nucleotides are no longer added to the RNA chain and therefore terminating elongation of that chain, and as a result affects the transcription process.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] This process occurs when dCas9 is mass-produced so it is able to affect the most genes at any given time via a sequence specific guide RNA molecule.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] Since dCas9 appears to down regulate gene expression, this action is amplified even more when it is used in conjunction with repressive chromatin modifier domains.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] The dCas9 protein has other functions outside of the regulation of gene expression.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] A promoter can be added to the dCas9 protein which allows them to work with each other to become efficient at beginning or stopping transcription at different sequences along a strand of DNA.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] These two proteins are specific in where they act on a gene.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] This is prevalent in certain types of prokaryotes when a promoter and dCas9 align themselves together to impede the ability of elongation of polymer of nucleotides coming together to form a transcribed piece of DNA.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] Without the promoter, the dCas9 protein does not have the same effect by itself or with a gene body.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] When examining the effects of repression of transcription further, H3K27, an amino acid component of a histone, becomes methylated through the interaction of dCas9 and a peptide called FOG1.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] Essentially, this interaction causes gene repression on the C + N terminal section of the amino acid complex at the specific junction of the gene, and as a result, terminates transcription.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] dCas9 also proves to be efficient when it comes to altering certain proteins that can create diseases.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] When the dCas9 attaches to a form of RNA called guide-RNA, it prevents the proliferation of repeating codons and DNA sequences that might be harmful to an organism's genome.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] Further explanation of how the dCas9 protein works can be found in their utilization of plant genomes by the regulation of gene production in plants to either increase or decrease certain characteristics.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] The CRISPR-CAS9 system has the ability to either upregulate or downregulate genes.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] The dCas9 proteins are a component of the CRISPR-CAS9 system and these proteins can repress certain areas of a plant gene.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] This happens when dCAS9 binds to repressor domains, and in the case of the plants, deactivation of a regulatory gene such as AtCSTF64, does occur.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] Bacteria are another focus of the usage of dCas9 proteins as well.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] Since eukaryotes have a larger DNA makeup and genome; the much smaller bacteria are easy to manipulate.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] As a result, eukaryotes use dCas9 to inhibit RNA polymerase from continuing the process of transcription of genetic material.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] Cas9 features a bi-lobed architecture with the guide RNA nestled between the alpha-helical lobe (blue) and the nuclease lobe (cyan, orange, and gray).
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] These two lobes are connected through a single bridge helix.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] There are two nuclease domains located in the multi-domain nuclease lobe, the RuvC (gray) which cleaves the non-target DNA strand, and the HNH nuclease domain (cyan) that cleaves the target strand of DNA.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] The RuvC domain is encoded by sequentially disparate sites that interact in the tertiary structure to form the RuvC cleavage domain (See right figure).
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] A key feature of the target DNA is that it must contain a protospacer adjacent motif (PAM) consisting of the three-nucleotide sequence- NGG.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] This PAM is recognized by the PAM-interacting domain (PI domain, orange) located near the C-terminal end of Cas9.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] Cas9 undergoes distinct conformational changes between the apo (apoenzyme), guide RNA bound, and guide RNA:DNA bound states.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] Cas9 recognizes the stem-loop architecture inherent in the CRISPR locus, which mediates the maturation of crRNA-tracrRNA ribonucleoprotein complex.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] Cas9 in complex with CRISPR RNA (crRNA) and trans-activating crRNA (tracrRNA) further recognizes and degrades the target dsDNA.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] In the co-crystal structure shown here, the crRNA-tracrRNA complex is replaced by a chimeric single-guide RNA (sgRNA, in red) which has been proved to have the same function as the natural RNA complex.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] The sgRNA base paired with target ssDNA is anchored by Cas9 as a T-shaped architecture.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] This crystal structure of the DNA-bound Cas9 enzyme reveals distinct conformational changes in the alpha-helical lobe with respect to the nuclease lobe, as well as the location of the HNH domain.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] The protein consists of a recognition lobe (REC) and a nuclease lobe (NUC).
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] All regions except the HNH form tight interactions with each other and sgRNA-ssDNA complex, while the HNH domain forms few contacts with the rest of the protein.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] In another conformation of Cas9 complex observed in the crystal, the HNH domain is not visible.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] These structures suggest the conformational flexibility of HNH domain.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] To date, at least three crystal structures have been studied and published.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] One representing a conformation of Cas9 in the apo state, and two representing Cas9 in the DNA bound state.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] In sgRNA-Cas9 complex, based on the crystal structure, REC1, BH and PI domains have important contacts with backbone or bases in both repeat and spacer region.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] Several Cas9 mutants including REC1 or REC2 domains deletion and residues mutations in BH have been tested.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] REC1 and BH related mutants show lower or none activity compared with wild type, which indicate these two domains are crucial for the sgRNA recognition at repeat sequence and stabilization of the whole complex.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] Although the interactions between spacer sequence and Cas9 as well as PI domain and repeat region need further studies, the co-crystal demonstrates clear interface between Cas9 and sgRNA.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] Cas9 contains two nuclease domains an McrA-like HNH nuclease domain and a RuvC-like nuclease domain.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] These HNH domain cleaves the complementary (target) DNA strand, while the RuvC-like nuclease domains are responsible for cleavage of the non-complementary (non-target DNA strands).
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] Despite low sequence similarity, the region homologous to RNase H adopts a RuvC fold and the HNH region folds similarly to T4 Endo VII, a member of the HNH endonuclease family.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] Wild-type *Streptococcus pyogenes* Cas9 requires magnesium (Mg2+) cofactors for RNA-mediated DNA cleavage, although varying levels of activity has been observed in the presence of other divalent metal ions.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] For example, in the presence of manganese (Mn2+), Cas9 has been shown to be exhibit RNA-independent DNA cleavage.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] DNA cleavage requires the presence of a protospacer adjacent motif (PAM) located at the non-target strand three nucleotides downstream from the cleavage site.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] Pyogenes* Cas9 is NGG, but alternative motifs like NAG and NGA are tolerated with lower cleavage activity.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] relatively rapid (*k* ≥ 700 s−1), the release of the cleavage products is very slow (*t*1/2 = ln(2)/*k* ≈ 43–91 h), essentially rendering Cas9 a single-turnover enzyme.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] Additional studies regarding the kinetics of Cas9 have shown engineered Cas9 to be effective in reducing off-target effects by modifying the rate of the reaction.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] Cleavage efficiency depends on several factors, including PAM recognition, nucleotide composition of the 20 nucleotide spacer-complementary region of the gRNAm.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] The most relevant nucleotide composition properties that impact efficiency are those in the PAM-proximal region.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] Free energy changes of nucleic acids are also highly relevant in defining cleavage activity.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] Guide RNAs that bind to the DNA forming a duplex that falls into a restricted range of binding free energy changes that excludes extremely weak or stable bindings generally perform efficiently.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] Stable guide RNA folding conformations can also impair cleavage.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] The seminal structural characterization of the nuclease demonstrated that the HNH domain precisely cleaves between the positions 18 and 17 (18|17) of the protospacer, while the RuvC cleaves the non-target strand at corresponding and downstream positions.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] Molecular dynamics simulations reported that cleavage of the NTS between 17|16 of the target sequence was more energetically favored than 18|17, generating 1 nucleotide 5' ssDNA overhangs.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] Notably, the authors demonstrated that the 5' overhangs are filled in during DNA repair, resulting in templated insertions, where the 5' overhang is used as a template by Pol4 for the repair reaction.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] The association between staggered cleavage and precise templated insertions have been supported by additional studies in human cells.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] The nucleotide composition of the five bases closest to the PAM in the target sequence also affects the scission profile, influencing whether DNA cleavage is blunt or staggered.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] In 2024 a high-throughput investigation of Cas9 scission profile revealed that ~85% of on-target cleavage is blunt, whereas ~15% had a 1 nucleotide 5' overhang.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] Off-targets had a higher staggered cleavage rate compared to on-target sites, with approximately 1/3 of off-targets displaying 5' overhangs from 1 to 3 nucleotides.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] Sequence patterns within the target region were shown to favor the formation of either blunt or staggered DNA cuts, and staggered cleavage was associated with the formation of predictable insertion-deletion (indel) outcomes.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] Most archaea and bacteria stubbornly refuse to allow a Cas9 to edit their genome.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] This is because they can attach foreign DNA, that does not affect them, into their genome.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] Another way that these cells defy Cas9 is by process of restriction modification (RM) system.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] When a bacteriophage enters a bacteria or archaea cell it is targeted by the RM system.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] The RM system then cuts the bacteriophages DNA into separate pieces by restriction enzymes and uses endonucleases to further destroy the strands of DNA.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] This poses a problem to Cas9 editing because the RM system also targets the foreign genes added by the Cas9 process.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] Due to the unique ability of Cas9 to bind to essentially any complement sequence in any genome, researchers wanted to use this enzyme to repress transcription of various genomic loci.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] To accomplish this, the two crucial catalytic residues of the RuvC and HNH domain can be mutated to alanine abolishing all endonuclease activity of Cas9.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] The resulting protein coined 'dead' Cas9 or 'dCas9' for short, can still tightly bind to dsDNA.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] This catalytically inactive Cas9 variant has been used for both mechanistic studies into Cas9 DNA interrogative binding and as a general programmable DNA binding RNA-Protein complex.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] Also, dCas9 can be targeted to the coding region of loci such that inhibition of RNA Polymerase occurs during the elongation phase of transcription.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] In Eukaryotes, silencing of gene expression can be extended by targeting dCas9 to enhancer sequences, where dCas9 can block assembly of transcription factors leading to silencing of specific gene expression.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] This technology is similar in principle to RNAi such that gene expression is being modulated at the RNA level.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] However, the dCas9 approach has gained much traction as there exist less off-target effects and in general larger and more reproducible silencing effects through the use of dCas9 compared to RNAi screens.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] Furthermore, because the dCas9 approach to gene silencing can be quantitatively controlled, a researcher can now precisely control the extent to which a gene of interest is repressed allowing more questions about gene regulation and gene stoichiometry to be answered.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] Beyond direct binding of dCas9 to transcriptionally sensitive positions of loci, dCas9 can be fused to a variety of modulatory protein domains to carry out a myriad of functions.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] Recently, dCas9 has been fused to chromatin remodeling proteins (HDACs/HATs) to reorganize the chromatin structure around various loci.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] This is important in targeting various eukaryotic genes of interest as heterochromatin structures hinder Cas9 binding.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] Furthermore, because Cas9 can react to heterochromatin, it is theorized that this enzyme can be further applied to studying the chromatin structure of various loci.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] Additionally, dCas9 has been employed in genome wide screens of gene repression.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] By employing large libraries of guide RNAs capable of targeting thousands of genes, genome wide genetic screens using dCas9 have been conducted.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] Another method for silencing transcription with Cas9 is to directly cleave mRNA products with the catalytically active Cas9 enzyme.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] This approach is made possible by hybridizing ssDNA with a PAM complement sequence to ssRNA allowing for a dsDNA-RNA PAM site for Cas9 binding.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] This technology makes available the ability to isolate endogenous RNA transcripts in cells without the need to induce chemical modifications to RNA or RNA tagging methods.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] In contrast to silencing genes, dCas9 can also be used to activate genes when fused to transcription activating factors.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] These factors include subunits of bacterial RNA Polymerase II and traditional transcription factors in eukaryotes.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/cas9] Recently, genome-wide screens of transcription activation have also been accomplished using dCas9 fusions named 'CRISPRa' for activation.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] Cas9 (or "CRISPR-associated protein 9") is an enzyme that uses CRISPR sequences as a guide to recognize and open up specific strands of DNA that are complementary to the CRISPR sequence.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] Cas9 enzymes together with CRISPR sequences form the basis of a technology known as CRISPR-Cas9 that can be used to edit genes within living organisms.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] This editing process has a wide variety of applications including basic biological research, development of biotechnological products, and treatment of diseases.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] The development of the CRISPR-Cas9 genome editing technique was recognized by the Nobel Prize in Chemistry in 2020 awarded to Emmanuelle Charpentier and Jennifer Doudna.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] The discovery of clustered DNA repeats took place independently in three parts of the world.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] The first description of what would later be called CRISPR is Ishino, et al. in 1987.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] They accidentally cloned part of a CRISPR sequence together with the iap *gene* *(*isozyme conversion of alkaline phosphatase*)* from *Escherichia coli*.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] The organization of the repeats surprised them, as clustered repeated sequences are more typically arranged consecutively, without interspersing sequences.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] In 1993, van Solingen et al., published two articles about a cluster of interrupted direct repeats (DR) in that bacterium.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] The team recognized the diversity of the sequences that intervened in the direct repeats among different strains of *M. tuberculosis* and used this property to design a typing method called *spoligotyping*, which remains in use.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] Mojica studied the function of repeats in the archaeal genera *Haloferax* and *Haloarcula*.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] Mojica's supervisor surmised that the clustered repeats had a role in segregating replicated DNA into daughter cells during cell division, because plasmids and chromosomes with identical repeat arrays could not coexist in *Haloferax volcanii*.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] They noted the transcription of the interrupted repeats for the first time; CRISPR's first full characterization.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] By 2000, Mojica and his students, after an automated search of published genomes, identified interrupted repeats in 20 species of microbes as belonging to the same family.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] Because those sequences were interspaced, Mojica initially called these sequences "short regularly spaced repeats" (SRSR).
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] In 2001, Mojica and Jansen, who were searching for additional interrupted repeats, proposed the acronym CRISPR (Clustered Regularly Interspaced Short Palindromic Repeats) to encompass the numerous acronyms then in use.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] In 2002, Tang, et al. showed evidence that CRISPR repeat regions in *Archaeoglobus fulgidus* were transcribed into long RNA molecules subsequently processed into unit-length small RNAs, plus some longer forms of 2, 3, or more spacer-repeat units.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] In 2005, Barrangou discovered that *S thermophilus*, after iterative phage infection challenges, develops increased phage resistance due to the incorporation of additional CRISPR spacer sequences.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] A major advance came with Jansen's observation that the prokaryote repeat cluster was accompanied by four homologous genes, CRISPR-associated systems, *Cas* 1–4.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] The Cas proteins showed helicase and nuclease motifs, suggesting a role in the dynamic structure of the CRISPR loci.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] However, CRISPR's function remained enigmatic.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] In 2005, three independent research groups showed that some CRISPR spacers are derived from phage DNA and extrachromosomal DNA such as plasmids.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] In effect, the spacers are fragments of DNA gathered from viruses that previously attacked the cell.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] The source of the spacers was a sign that the CRISPR-*cas* system could have a role in adaptive immunity in bacteria.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] All three studies proposing this idea were initially rejected by high-profile journals, but eventually appeared elsewhere.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] The first publication proposing a role of CRISPR-Cas in microbial immunity, by Mojica, et al., predicted a role for the RNA transcript of spacers on target recognition in a mechanism that could be analogous to the RNA interference system used by eukaryotic cells.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] Koonin and colleagues extended this RNA interference hypothesis by proposing mechanisms of action for the different CRISPR-Cas subtypes according to the predicted function of their proteins.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] Experimental work by several groups revealed the basic mechanisms of CRISPR-Cas immunity.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] In 2007, the first experimental evidence that CRISPR was part of the adaptive immune system was published.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] A CRISPR region in *Streptococcus thermophilus* acquired spacers from the DNA of an infecting bacteriophage.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] The researchers manipulated the resistance of *S. thermophilus* to different types of phages by adding and deleting spacers whose sequence matched those found in the phages.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] In 2008, Brouns and Van der Oost identified a complex of Cas proteins called Cascade, that in *E. coli* cut the CRISPR RNA precursor within the repeats into mature spacer-containing RNA molecules called CRISPR RNA (crRNA), which remained bound to the protein complex.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] Cascade, crRNA and a helicase/nuclease (Cas3) were required to provide a bacterial host with immunity against infection by a DNA virus.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] By designing an anti-virus CRISPR, they demonstrated that two orientations of the crRNA (sense/antisense) provided immunity, indicating that the crRNA guides were targeting dsDNA.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] That year Marraffini and Sontheimer confirmed that a CRISPR sequence of *S. epidermidis* targeted DNA and not RNA to prevent conjugation.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] This finding was at odds with the proposed RNA-interference-like mechanism of CRISPR-Cas immunity, although a CRISPR-Cas system that targets foreign RNA was later found in *Pyrococcus furiosus*.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] A 2010 study reported that CRISPR-Cas cuts strands of both phage and plasmid DNA in *S. thermophilus*.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] In 2012, Jinek et al. fused crRNA and tracrRNA into a single-guide RNA, simplifying Cas9 targeting. Šikšnys, et al., reported that Cas9 from *S. thermophilus* can target specific DNA by altering crRNA.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] In 2013, Cong, et al., as well as Mali, et al., applied CRISPR-Cas9 to edit human cell cultures.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] In 2015, Liang, et al., edited human tripronuclear zygotes, achieving successful cleavage in 28 of 54 embryos.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] Cas12a (CRISPR-associated protein 12a, previously Cpf1) is a Class II Type V CRISPR-associated endonuclease-exonuclease.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] In bacteria such as *F. novicida,* its natural context, Cas12a targets and destroys the genetic material of viruses and other foreign mobile genetic elements.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] In a target organism, crRNA contains a constant region that Cas12a recognizes and a "spacer" region that is complementary to a piece of foreign nucleic acid (e.g., a portion of a phage genome) that previously infected the cell.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] Originally introduced by the Jain lab in pre-print, modified versions of Class II systems (specifically Cas12a) function with an artificial single-stranded DNA guide in place of natural RNA.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] Within this new paradigm, the system's endonuclease activity now is redirected towards cleaving ssRNA instead of dsDNA.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] With DNA as the guide, the need for intricate RNA preparation and preservation is no longer required, allowing Class II effectors more versatility in programmable RNA targeting and translational biotechnology.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] Cas13 is a family of orthologous CRISPR-associated endonucleases that target RNA (unlike Cas9 and Cas12, which target DNA).
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] Cas13 utilizes a single RNA-guided endonuclease to bind and cleave specific ssRNA sequences.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] It employs two distinct ribonuclease functions: one processes its own CRISPR RNA (crRNA) and another degrades the target RNA.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] The system's specificity allows for the correction of mutations at the transcript level.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] Cas13 remains bound to the target and then cleaves other ssRNA molecules non-discriminately.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] This collateral cleavage property is exploited in the development of various diagnostic technologies.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] Its PAM-independent targeting and reduced off-target effects make it suitable for RNA imaging, phage genome engineering, and transient gene regulation.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] The CRISPR array is made up of an AT-rich leader sequence followed by short repeats that are separated by unique spacers.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] CRISPR repeats typically range in size from 28 to 37 base pairs (bps), though there can be as few as 23 bp and as many as 55 bp.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] Some show dyad symmetry, implying the formation of a secondary structure such as a stem-loop ('hairpin') in the RNA, while others are designed to be unstructured.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] The size of spacers in different CRISPR arrays is typically 32 to 38 bp (range 21 to 72 bp).
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] New spacers can appear rapidly as part of the immune response to phage infection.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] There are usually fewer than 50 units of the repeat-spacer sequence in a CRISPR array.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] Small clusters of *cas* genes are often located next to CRISPR repeat-spacer arrays.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] Collectively the 93 *cas* genes are grouped into 35 families based on sequence similarity of the encoded proteins.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] 11 of the 35 families form the *cas* core, which includes the protein families Cas1 through Cas9.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] A complete CRISPR-Cas locus has at least one gene belonging to the *cas* core.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] CRISPR-Cas systems fall into two classes.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] Class 1 systems use a complex of multiple Cas proteins to degrade foreign nucleic acids.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] Class 2 systems use a single large Cas protein for the same purpose.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] Class 1 is divided into types I, III, and IV; class 2 is divided into types II, V, and VI.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] The 6 system types are divided into 33 subtypes.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] Each type and most subtypes are characterized by a "signature gene" found almost exclusively in the category.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] Classification is also based on the complement of *cas* genes that are present.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] Most CRISPR-Cas systems have a Cas1 protein.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] The phylogeny of Cas1 proteins generally agrees with the classification system, but exceptions exist due to module shuffling.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] Many organisms contain multiple CRISPR-Cas systems suggesting that they are compatible and may share components.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] The sporadic distribution of the CRISPR-Cas subtypes suggests that the CRISPR-Cas system is subject to horizontal gene transfer during microbial evolution.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] CRISPR-Cas immunity is a natural process of bacteria and archaea.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] CRISPR-Cas prevents bacteriophage infection, conjugation and natural transformation by degrading foreign nucleic acids that enter the cell.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] When a microbe is invaded by a bacteriophage, the first stage of the immune response is to capture phage DNA and insert it into a CRISPR locus in the form of a spacer.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] Cas1 and Cas2 are found in both types of CRISPR-Cas immune systems, which indicates that they are involved in spacer acquisition.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] Mutation studies confirmed this hypothesis, showing that removal of Cas1 or Cas2 stopped spacer acquisition, without affecting CRISPR immune response.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] Multiple Cas1 proteins have been characterised and their structures resolved.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] Cas1 proteins have diverse amino acid sequences.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] However, their crystal structures are similar and all purified Cas1 proteins are metal-dependent nucleases/integrases that bind to DNA in a sequence-independent manner.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] Representative Cas2 proteins have been characterised and possess either (single strand) ssRNA- or (double strand) dsDNA- specific endoribonuclease activity.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] In the I-E system of *E. coli*, Cas1 and Cas2 form a complex where a Cas2 dimer bridges two Cas1 dimers.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] In this complex, Cas2 performs a non-enzymatic scaffolding role, binding double-stranded fragments of invading DNA, while Cas1 binds the single-stranded flanks of the DNA and catalyses their integration into CRISPR arrays.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] New spacers are usually added at the beginning of the CRISPR next to the leader sequence creating a chronological record of viral infections.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] In *E. coli* a histone like protein called integration host factor (IHF), which binds to the leader sequence, is responsible for the accuracy of this integration.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] Bioinformatic analysis of regions of phage genomes that were excised as spacers (termed protospacers) revealed that they were not randomly selected but instead were found adjacent to short (3–5 bp) DNA sequences termed protospacer adjacent motifs (PAM).
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] Analysis of CRISPR-Cas systems showed PAMs to be important for type I and type II, but not type III systems during acquisition.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] In type I and type II systems, protospacers are excised at positions adjacent to a PAM sequence, with the other end of the spacer cut using a ruler mechanism, thus maintaining the regularity of the spacer size in the CRISPR array.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] The conservation of the PAM sequence differs between CRISPR-Cas systems and appears to be evolutionarily linked to Cas1 and the leader sequence.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] New spacers are added to a CRISPR array in a directional manner, occurring preferentially, but not exclusively, adjacent to the leader sequence.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] Analysis of the type I-E system from *E. coli* demonstrated that the first direct repeat adjacent to the leader sequence is copied, with the newly acquired spacer inserted between the first and second direct repeats.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] The PAM sequence appears to be important during spacer insertion in type I-E systems.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] That sequence contains a strongly conserved final nucleotide (nt) adjacent to the first nt of the protospacer.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] This nt becomes the final base in the first direct repeat.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] This suggests that the spacer acquisition machinery generates single-stranded overhangs in the second-to-last position of the direct repeat and in the PAM during spacer insertion.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] However, not all CRISPR-Cas systems appear to share this mechanism as PAMs in other organisms do not show the same level of conservation in the final position.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] It is likely that in those systems, a blunt end is generated at the very end of the direct repeat and the protospacer during acquisition.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] Analysis of *Sulfolobus solfataricus* CRISPRs revealed further complexities to the canonical model of spacer insertion, as one of its six CRISPR loci inserted new spacers randomly throughout its CRISPR array, as opposed to inserting closest to the leader sequence.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] Multiple CRISPRs contain many spacers to the same phage.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] The mechanism that causes this phenomenon was discovered in the type I-E system of *E. coli*.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] A significant enhancement in spacer acquisition was detected where spacers already target the phage, even mismatches to the protospacer.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] This 'priming' requires the Cas proteins involved in both acquisition and interference to interact with each other.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] Newly acquired spacers that result from the priming mechanism are always found on the same strand as the priming spacer.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] This observation led to the hypothesis that the acquisition machinery slides along the foreign DNA after priming to find a new protospacer.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] CRISPR-RNA (crRNA), which later guides the Cas nuclease to the target during the interference step, must be generated from the CRISPR sequence.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] The crRNA is initially transcribed as part of a single long transcript encompassing much of the CRISPR array.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] This transcript is then cleaved by Cas proteins to form crRNAs.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] The mechanism to produce crRNAs differs among CRISPR-Cas systems.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] In type I-E and type I-F systems, the proteins Cas6e and Cas6f respectively, recognise stem-loops created by the pairing of identical repeats that flank the crRNA.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] These Cas proteins cleave the longer transcript at the edge of the paired region, leaving a single crRNA along with a small remnant of the paired repeat region.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] Type III systems also use Cas6, however, their repeats do not produce stem-loops.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] Cleavage instead occurs by the longer transcript wrapping around the Cas6 to allow cleavage just upstream of the repeat sequence.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] Type II systems lack the Cas6 gene and instead utilize RNaseIII for cleavage.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] Functional type II systems encode an extra small RNA that is complementary to the repeat sequence, known as a trans-activating crRNA (tracrRNA).
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] Transcription of the tracrRNA and the primary CRISPR transcript results in base pairing and the formation of dsRNA at the repeat sequence, which is subsequently targeted by RNaseIII to produce crRNAs.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] Unlike the other two systems, the crRNA does not contain the full spacer, which is instead truncated at one end.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] CrRNAs associate with Cas proteins to form ribonucleotide complexes that recognize foreign nucleic acids.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] CrRNAs show no preference between the coding and non-coding strands, which is indicative of an RNA-guided DNA-targeting system.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] The type I-E complex (commonly referred to as Cascade) requires five Cas proteins bound to a single crRNA.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] During the interference stage in type I systems, the PAM sequence is recognized on the crRNA-complementary strand and is required along with crRNA annealing.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] In type I systems correct base pairing between the crRNA and the protospacer signals a conformational change in Cascade that recruits Cas3 for DNA degradation.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] Type II systems rely on a single multifunctional protein, Cas9, for the interference step.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] Cas9 requires both the crRNA and the tracrRNA to function and cleave DNA using its dual HNH and RuvC/RNaseH-like endonuclease domains.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] Basepairing between the PAM and the phage genome is required in type II systems.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] However, the PAM is recognized on the same strand as the crRNA (the opposite strand to type I systems).
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] Type III systems, like type I require six or seven Cas proteins binding to crRNAs.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] The type III systems analysed from *S. solfataricus* and *P. furiosus* both target the mRNA of phages rather than phage DNA genome, which may make these systems uniquely capable of targeting RNA-based phage genomes.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] Type III systems were also found to target DNA in addition to RNA using a different Cas protein in the complex, Cas10.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] The DNA cleavage was shown to be transcription dependent.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] The mechanism for distinguishing self from foreign DNA during interference is built into the crRNAs and is therefore likely common to all three systems.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] Throughout the distinctive maturation process of each major type, all crRNAs contain a spacer sequence and some portion of the repeat at one or both ends.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] It is the partial repeat sequence that prevents the CRISPR-Cas system from targeting the chromosome as base pairing beyond the spacer sequence signals self and prevents DNA cleavage.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] RNA-guided CRISPR enzymes are classified as type V restriction enzymes.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] The cas genes in the adaptor and effector modules of the CRISPR-Cas system are believed to have evolved from two different ancestral modules.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] A transposon-like element called casposon encoding the Cas1-like integrase and potentially other components of the adaptation module was inserted next to the ancestral effector module, which likely functioned as an independent innate immune system.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] The highly conserved cas1 and cas2 genes of the adaptor module evolved from the ancestral module while a variety of class 1 effector cas genes evolved from the ancestral effector module.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] The evolution of these various class 1 effector module cas genes was guided by various mechanisms, such as duplication events.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] On the other hand, each type of class 2 effector module arose from subsequent independent insertions of mobile genetic elements.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] These mobile genetic elements took the place of the multiple gene effector modules to create single gene effector modules that produce large proteins which perform all the necessary tasks of the effector module.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] The spacer regions of CRISPR-Cas systems are taken directly from foreign mobile genetic elements and thus their long-term evolution is hard to trace.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] The non-random evolution of these spacer regions has been found to be highly dependent on the environment and the particular foreign mobile genetic elements it contains.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] CRISPR-Cas can immunize bacteria against certain phages and thus halt transmission.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] For this reason, Koonin described CRISPR-Cas as a Lamarckian inheritance mechanism.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] However, this was disputed by a critic who noted, "We should remember [Lamarck] for the good he contributed to science, not for things that resemble his theory only superficially.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] Indeed, thinking of CRISPR and other phenomena as Lamarckian only obscures the simple and elegant way evolution really works".
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] But as more recent studies have been conducted, it has become apparent that the acquired spacer regions of CRISPR-Cas systems are indeed a form of Lamarckian evolution because they are genetic mutations that are acquired and then passed on.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] On the other hand, the evolution of the Cas gene machinery that facilitates the system evolves through classic Darwinian evolution.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] Analysis of CRISPR sequences revealed coevolution of host and viral genomes.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] The basic model of CRISPR evolution is newly incorporated spacers driving phages to mutate their genomes to avoid the bacterial immune response, creating diversity in both the phage and host populations.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] To resist a phage infection, the sequence of the CRISPR spacer must correspond perfectly to the sequence of the target phage gene.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] Phages can continue to infect their hosts' given point mutations in the spacer.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] Similar stringency is required in PAM or the bacterial strain remains phage sensitive.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] A study of 124 *S. thermophilus* strains showed that 26% of all spacers were unique and that different CRISPR loci showed different rates of spacer acquisition.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] Some CRISPR loci evolve more rapidly than others, which allowed the strains' phylogenetic relationships to be determined.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] A comparative genomic analysis showed that *E. coli* and *S. enterica* evolve much more slowly than *S. thermophilus*.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] The latter's strains that diverged 250,000 years ago still contained the same spacer complement.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] Metagenomic analysis of two acid-mine-drainage biofilms showed that one of the analyzed CRISPRs contained extensive deletions and spacer additions versus the other biofilm, suggesting a higher phage activity/prevalence in one community than the other.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] In the oral cavity, a temporal study determined that 7–22% of spacers were shared over 17 months within an individual while less than 2% were shared across individuals.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] From the same environment, a single strain was tracked using PCR primers specific to its CRISPR system.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] Broad-level results of spacer presence/absence showed significant diversity.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] However, this CRISPR added three spacers over 17 months, suggesting that even in an environment with significant CRISPR diversity some loci evolve slowly.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] CRISPRs were analysed from the metagenomes produced for the Human Microbiome Project.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] Although most were body-site specific, some within a body site are widely shared among individuals.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] One of these loci originated from streptococcal species and contained ≈15,000 spacers, 50% of which were unique.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] Similar to the targeted studies of the oral cavity, some showed little evolution over time.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] CRISPR evolution was studied in chemostats using *S. thermophilus* to directly examine spacer acquisition rates.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] In one week, *S. thermophilus* strains acquired up to three spacers when challenged with a single phage.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] During the same interval, the phage developed single-nucleotide polymorphisms that became fixed in the population, suggesting that targeting had prevented phage replication absent these mutations.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] Another *S. thermophilus* experiment showed that phages can infect and replicate in hosts that have only one targeting spacer.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] Yet another showed that sensitive hosts can exist in environments with high-phage titres.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] The chemostat and observational studies suggest many nuances to CRISPR and phage (co)evolution.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] CRISPRs are widely distributed among bacteria and archaea and show some sequence similarities.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] Their most notable characteristic is their repeating spacers and direct repeats.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] This characteristic makes CRISPRs easily identifiable in long sequences of DNA, since the number of repeats decreases the likelihood of a false positive match.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] Analysis of CRISPRs in metagenomic data is more challenging, as CRISPR loci do not typically assemble, due to their repetitive nature or through strain variation, which confuses assembly algorithms.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] Where many reference genomes are available, polymerase chain reaction (PCR) can be used to amplify CRISPR arrays and analyse spacer content.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] However, this approach yields information only for specifically targeted CRISPRs and for organisms with sufficient representation in public databases to design reliable polymerase PCR primers.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] Degenerate repeat-specific primers can be used to amplify CRISPR spacers directly from environmental samples; amplicons containing two or three spacers can be then computationally assembled to reconstruct long CRISPR arrays.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] The alternative is to extract and reconstruct CRISPR arrays from shotgun metagenomic data.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] This is computationally more difficult, particularly with second generation sequencing technologies (e.g.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] 454, Illumina), as the short read lengths prevent more than two or three repeat units appearing in a single read.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] Another way for bacteria to defend against phage infection is by having chromosomal islands.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] A subtype of chromosomal islands called phage-inducible chromosomal island (PICI) is excised from a bacterial chromosome upon phage infection and can inhibit phage replication.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] PICIs are induced, excised, replicated, and finally packaged into small capsids by certain staphylococcal temperate phages.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] PICIs use several mechanisms to block phage reproduction.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] In the first mechanism, PICI-encoded Ppi differentially blocks phage maturation by binding or interacting specifically with phage TerS, hence blocking phage TerS/TerL complex formation responsible for phage DNA packaging.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] In the second mechanism PICI CpmAB redirects the phage capsid morphogenetic protein to make 95% of SaPI-sized capsid and phage DNA can package only 1/3rd of their genome in these small capsids and hence become nonviable phage.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] The third mechanism involves two proteins, PtiA and PtiB, that target the LtrC, which is responsible for the production of virion and lysis proteins.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] This interference mechanism is modulated by a modulatory protein, PtiM, binds to one of the interference-mediating proteins, PtiA, and hence achieves the required level of interference.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] One study showed that lytic ICP1 phage, which specifically targets *Vibrio cholerae* serogroup O1, has acquired a CRISPR-Cas system that targets a *V. cholera* PICI-like element.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] The system has 2 CRISPR loci and 9 Cas genes.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] It seems to be homologous to the I-F system found in *Yersinia pestis*.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] Moreover, like the bacterial CRISPR-Cas system, ICP1 CRISPR-Cas can acquire new sequences, which allows phage and host to co-evolve.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] Certain archaeal viruses were shown to carry mini-CRISPR arrays containing one or two spacers.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] It has been shown that spacers within the virus-borne CRISPR arrays target other viruses and plasmids, suggesting that mini-CRISPR arrays represent a mechanism of heterotypic superinfection exclusion and participate in interviral conflicts.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] CRISPR gene editing is a revolutionary technology that allows for precise, targeted modifications to the DNA of living organisms.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] Developed from a natural defense mechanism found in bacteria, CRISPR-Cas9 is the most commonly used system.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] Gene editing with CRISPR-Cas9 involves a Cas9 nuclease and an engineered guide RNA, which come together to allow for the precise "cutting" of one or both strands of DNA at specific locations within the genome.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] It makes use of the cell's natural DNA repair systems, including non-homologous end joining, homology-directed repair, or mismatch repair, to modify, insert, or delete genetic material at these specific cut sites.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] This technology has transformed fields such as genetics, medicine, and agriculture, offering potential treatments for genetic disorders, advancements in crop engineering, and research into the fundamental workings of life.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] However, its ethical implications and potential unintended consequences have sparked significant debate.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] In February of 2025 the first case of CRISPR gene editing therapy on a child was documented.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] It was used to treat Severe Carbamoyl Phosphate Synthetase 1 Deficiency.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/crispr] It was administered At Children's Hospital of Philadelphia and is currently successful in its use to counteract the disease.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/guide-rna] The RNA editing guide RNA was discovered in 1990 by B.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/guide-rna] Simpson through Northern Blot Hybridization in the mitochondrial maxicircle DNA of the eukaryotic parasite Leishmania tarentolae.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/guide-rna] Subsequent research throughout the mid-2000s and the following years explored the structure and function of gRNA and the CRISPR-Cas system.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/guide-rna] A significant breakthrough occurred in 2012 when it was discovered that gRNA could guide the Cas9 endonuclease to introduce target-specific cuts in double-stranded DNA.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/guide-rna] This discovery led to the 2020 Nobel Prize in Chemistry awarded to Jennifer Doudna and Emmanuelle Charpentier for their contributions to the development of CRISPR-Cas9 gene-editing technology.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/guide-rna] Trypanosomatid protists and other kinetoplastids have a post-transcriptional RNA modification process known as "RNA editing" that performs a uridine insertion/deletion inside mitochondria.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/guide-rna] This mitochondrial DNA is circular and is divided into maxicircles and minicircles.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/guide-rna] A mitochondrion contains about 50 maxicircles which have both coding and non coding regions and consists of approximately 20 kilo bases (kb).
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/guide-rna] The coding region is highly conserved (16-17kb) and the non-coding region varies depending on the species.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/guide-rna] Minicircles are small (around 1 kb) but more numerous than maxicircles, a mitochondrion contains several thousands minicircles.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/guide-rna] Maxicircles can encode "cryptogenes" and some gRNAs; minicircles can encode the majority of gRNAs.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/guide-rna] Some gRNA genes show identical insertion and deletion sites even if they have different sequences, whereas other gRNA sequences are not complementary to pre-edited mRNA.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/guide-rna] Maxicircles and minicircles molecules are catenated into a giant network of DNA inside the mitochondrion.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/guide-rna] The majority of maxicircle transcripts cannot be translated into proteins due to frameshifts in their sequences.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/guide-rna] These frameshifts are corrected post-transcriptionally through the insertion and deletion of uridine residues at precise sites, which then create an open reading frame.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/guide-rna] This open reading frame is subsequently translated into a protein that is homologous to mitochondrial proteins found in other cells.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/guide-rna] The process of uridine insertion and deletion is mediated by short guide RNAs (gRNAs), which encode the editing information through complementary sequences, and allow for base pairing between guanine and uracil (GU) as well as between guanine and cytosine (GC), facilitating the editing process.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/guide-rna] Guide RNAs are mainly transcribed from the intergenic region of DNA maxicircle and have sequences complementary to mRNA.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/guide-rna] The 3' end of gRNAs contains an oligo 'U' tail (5-24 nucleotides in length) which is in a nonencoded region but interacts and forms a stable complex with A and G rich regions of pre-edited mRNA and gRNA, that are thermodynamically stabilized by a 5' and 3' anchors.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/guide-rna] This initial hybrid helps in the recognition of specific mRNA site to be edited.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/guide-rna] RNA editing typically progresses from the 3' to the 5' end on the mRNA.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/guide-rna] The initial editing process begins when a gRNA forms an RNA duplex with a complementary mRNA sequence located just downstream of the editing site.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/guide-rna] This pairing recruits a number of ribonucleoprotein complexes that direct the cleavage of the first mismatched base adjacent to the gRNA-mRNA anchor.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/guide-rna] Following this, Uridylyltransferase inserts a 'U' at the 3' end, and RNA ligase then joins the two severed ends.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/guide-rna] The process repeats at the next upstream editing site in a similar manner.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/guide-rna] A single gRNA usually encodes the information for several editing sites (an editing "block"), the editing of which produces a complete gRNA/mRNA duplex.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/guide-rna] This process of sequential editing is known as the enzyme cascade model.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/guide-rna] In the case of "pan-edited" mRNAs, the duplex unwinds and another gRNA forms a duplex with the edited mRNA sequence, initiating another round of editing.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/guide-rna] These overlapping gRNAs form an editing "domain".
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/guide-rna] Some genes contain multiple editing domains.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/guide-rna] The extent of editing for any particular gene varies among trypanosomatid species.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/guide-rna] The variation consists of the loss of editing at the 3' side, probably due to the loss of minicircle sequence classes that encode specific gRNAs.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/guide-rna] A retroposition model has been proposed to explain the partial, and in some cases, complete loss of editing through evolution.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/guide-rna] Although the loss of editing is typically lethal, such losses have been observed in old laboratory strains.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/guide-rna] The maintenance of editing over the long evolutionary history of these ancient protists suggests the presence of a selective advantage, the exact nature of which is still uncertain.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/guide-rna] It is not clear why trypanosomatids utilize such an elaborate mechanism to produce mRNAs.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/guide-rna] It might have originated in the early mitochondria of the ancestor of the kintoplastid protist lineage, since it is present in the bodonids which are ancestral to the trypanosomatids, and may not be present in the euglenoids, which branched from the same common ancestor as the kinetoplastids.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/guide-rna] In the protozoan *Leishmania tarentolae*, 12 of the 18 mitochondrial genes are edited using this process.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/guide-rna] The mRNA is actually edited twice in succession.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/guide-rna] The 3' end is used to anchor the gRNA (gCyb-I gRNA in this case) by basepairing (some G/U pairs are used).
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/guide-rna] The 5' end does not exactly match and one of three specific endonucleases cleaves the mRNA at the mismatch site.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/guide-rna] This particular gene has two overlapping gRNA editing sites.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/guide-rna] The 5' end of this section is the 3' anchor for another gRNA (gCyb-II gRNA).
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/guide-rna] Prokaryotes as bacteria and archaea, use CRISPR (clustered regularly interspaced short palindromic repeats) and its associated Cas enzymes, as their adaptive immune system.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/guide-rna] When prokaryotes are infected by phages, and manage to fend off the attack, specific Cas enzymes cut the phage DNA (or RNA) and integrate the fragments into the CRISPR sequence interspaces.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/guide-rna] These stored segments are then recognized during future virus attacks, allowing Cas enzymes to use RNA copies of these segments, along with their associated CRISPR sequences, as gRNA to identify and neutralize the foreign sequences.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/guide-rna] Guide RNA targets the complementary sequences by simple Watson-Crick base pairing.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/guide-rna] In the type II CRISPR/cas system, the sgRNA directs the Cas-enzyme to target specific regions in the genome for targeted DNA cleavage.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/guide-rna] The sgRNA is an artificially engineered combination of two RNA molecules: CRISPR RNA (crRNA) and trans-activating crRNA (tracrRNA).
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/guide-rna] The crRNA component is responsible for binding to the target-specific DNA region, while the tracrRNA component is responsible for the activation of the Cas9 endonuclease activity.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/guide-rna] These two components are linked by a short tetraloop structure, resulting in the formation of the sgRNA.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/guide-rna] The tracrRNA consist of base pairs that form a stem-loop structure, enabling its attachment to the endonuclease enzyme.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/guide-rna] The transcription of the CRISPR locus generates crRNA, which contains spacer regions flanked by repeat sequences, typically 18-20 base pairs (bp) in length.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/guide-rna] This crRNA guides the Cas9 endonuclease to the complementary target region on the DNA, where it cleaves the DNA, forming what is known as the effector complex.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/guide-rna] Modifications in the crRNA sequence within the sgRNA can alter the binding location, allowing for precise targeting of different DNA regions, effectively making it a programmable system for genome editing.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/guide-rna] The targeting specificity of CRISPR-Cas9 is determined by the 20-nucleotide (nt) sequence at the 5' end of the gRNA.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/guide-rna] The desired target sequence must precede the Protospacer Adjacent Motif (PAM), which is a short DNA sequence usually 2-6 base pairs in length that follows the DNA region targeted for cleavage by the CRISPR system, such as CRISPR-Cas9.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/guide-rna] The PAM is required for a Cas nuclease to cut and is usually located 3-4 nucleotides downstream from the cut site.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/guide-rna] Once the gRNA base pairs with the target, Cas9 induces a double-strand break about 3 nucleotides upstream of the PAM.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/guide-rna] The optimal GC content of the guide sequence should be over 50%.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/guide-rna] A higher GC content enhances the stability of the RNA-DNA duplex and reduces off-target hybridization.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/guide-rna] The length of guide sequences is typically 20 bp, but they can also range from 17 to 24 bp.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/guide-rna] A longer sequence minimizes off-target effects.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/guide-rna] Guide sequences shorter than 17 bp are at risk of targeting multiple loci.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/guide-rna] CRISPR (Clustered regularly interspaced short palindromic repeats)/Cas9 is a technique used for gene editing and gene therapy.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/guide-rna] Cas is an endonuclease enzyme that cuts DNA at a specific location directed by a guide RNA.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/guide-rna] This is a target-specific technique that can introduce gene knockouts or knock-ins depending on the double strand repair pathway.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/guide-rna] Evidence shows that both in vitro and in vivo, tracrRNA is required for Cas9 to bind to the target DNA sequence.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/guide-rna] The CRISPR-Cas9 system consists of three main stages.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/guide-rna] The first stage involves the extension of bases in the CRISPR locus region by addition of foreign DNA spacers in the genome sequence.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/guide-rna] Proteins like cas1 and cas2, assist in finding new spacers.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/guide-rna] The next stage involves transcription of CRISPR: pre-crRNA (precursor CRISPR RNA) are expressed by the transcription of CRISPR repeat-spacer array.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/guide-rna] Upon further modification, the pre-crRNA is converted to single spacer flanked regions forming short crRNA.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/guide-rna] RNA maturation process is similar in type I and III but different in type II.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/guide-rna] The third stage involves binding of cas9 protein and directing it to cleave the DNA segment.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/guide-rna] The Cas9 protein binds to a combined form of crRNA and tracrRNA forming an effector complex.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/guide-rna] This serves as guide RNA for the cas9 protein directing its endonuclease activity.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/guide-rna] One important method of gene regulation is RNA mutagenesis, which can be introduced through RNA editing with the assistance of gRNA.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/guide-rna] Guide RNA replaces adenosine with inosine at specific target sites, modifying the genetic code.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/guide-rna] Adenosine deaminase acts on RNA, bringing post transcriptional modification by altering codons and different protein functions.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/guide-rna] Guide RNAs are small nucleolar RNAs that, along with riboproteins, perform intracellular RNA alterations such as ribomethylation in rRNA and the introduction of pseudouridine in preribosomal RNA.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/guide-rna] Guide RNAs bind to the antisense RNA sequence and regulate RNA modification.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/guide-rna] It has been observed that small interfering RNA (siRNA) and micro RNA (miRNA) are generally used as target RNA sequences, and modifications are comparatively easy to introduce due to their small size.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/non-homologous-end-joining] NHEJ is typically guided by short homologous DNA sequences called microhomologies.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/non-homologous-end-joining] These microhomologies are often present in single-stranded overhangs on the ends of double-strand breaks.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/non-homologous-end-joining] When the overhangs are perfectly compatible, NHEJ usually repairs the break accurately.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/non-homologous-end-joining] Imprecise repair leading to loss of nucleotides can also occur, but is much more common when the overhangs are not compatible.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/non-homologous-end-joining] Inappropriate NHEJ can lead to translocations and telomere fusion, hallmarks of tumor cells.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/non-homologous-end-joining] NHEJ implementations are understood to have been existent throughout nearly all biological systems and it is the predominant double-strand break repair pathway in mammalian cells.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/non-homologous-end-joining] In budding yeast (*Saccharomyces cerevisiae*), however, homologous recombination dominates when the organism is grown under common laboratory conditions.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/non-homologous-end-joining] When the NHEJ pathway is inactivated, double-strand breaks can be repaired by a more error-prone pathway called microhomology-mediated end joining (MMEJ).
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/non-homologous-end-joining] In this pathway, end resection reveals short microhomologies on either side of the break, which are then aligned to guide repair.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/non-homologous-end-joining] This contrasts with classical NHEJ, which typically uses microhomologies already exposed in single-stranded overhangs on the DSB ends.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/non-homologous-end-joining] Repair by MMEJ therefore leads to deletion of the DNA sequence between the microhomologies.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/non-homologous-end-joining] Many species of bacteria, including *Escherichia coli*, lack an end joining pathway and thus rely completely on homologous recombination to repair double-strand breaks.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/non-homologous-end-joining] NHEJ proteins have been identified in a number of bacteria, including *Bacillus subtilis*, *Mycobacterium tuberculosis*, and *Mycobacterium smegmatis*.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/non-homologous-end-joining] Bacteria utilize a remarkably compact version of NHEJ in which all of the required activities are contained in only two proteins: a Ku homodimer and the multifunctional ligase/polymerase/nuclease LigD.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/non-homologous-end-joining] In mycobacteria, NHEJ is much more error prone than in yeast, with bases often added to and deleted from the ends of double-strand breaks during repair.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/non-homologous-end-joining] Many of the bacteria that possess NHEJ proteins spend a significant portion of their life cycle in a stationary haploid phase, in which a template for recombination is not available.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/non-homologous-end-joining] NHEJ may have evolved to help these organisms survive DSBs induced during desiccation.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/non-homologous-end-joining] It preferentially uses rNTPs (RNA nucleotides), possibly advantageous in dormant cells.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/non-homologous-end-joining] The archaeal NHEJ system in *Methanocella paludicola* have a homodimeric Ku, but the three functions of LigD are broken up into three single-domain proteins sharing an operon.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/non-homologous-end-joining] All three genes retain substantial homology with their LigD counterparts and the polymerase retains the preference for rNTP.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/non-homologous-end-joining] NHEJ has been lost and acquired multiple times in bacteria and archaea, with a significant amount of horizontal gene transfer shuffling the system around taxa.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/non-homologous-end-joining] Corndog and Omega, two related mycobacteriophages of *Mycobacterium smegmatis*, also encode Ku homologs and exploit the NHEJ pathway to recircularize their genomes during infection.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/non-homologous-end-joining] Unlike homologous recombination, which has been studied extensively in bacteria, NHEJ was originally discovered in eukaryotes and was only identified in prokaryotes in the past decade.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/non-homologous-end-joining] In yeast, the Mre11-Rad50-Xrs2 (MRX) complex is recruited to DSBs early and is thought to promote bridging of the DNA ends.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/non-homologous-end-joining] The corresponding mammalian complex of Mre11-Rad50-Nbs1 (MRN) is also involved in NHEJ, but it may function at multiple steps in the pathway beyond simply holding the ends in proximity.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/non-homologous-end-joining] DNA-PKcs is also thought to participate in end bridging during mammalian NHEJ.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/non-homologous-end-joining] Eukaryotic Ku is a heterodimer consisting of Ku70 and Ku80, and forms a complex with DNA-PKcs, which is present in mammals but absent in yeast.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/non-homologous-end-joining] Ku is a basket-shaped molecule that slides onto the DNA end and translocates inward.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/non-homologous-end-joining] Ku may function as a docking site for other NHEJ proteins, and is known to interact with the DNA ligase IV complex and XLF.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/non-homologous-end-joining] End processing involves removal of damaged or mismatched nucleotides by nucleases and resynthesis by DNA polymerases.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/non-homologous-end-joining] This step is not necessary if the ends are already compatible and have 3' hydroxyl and 5' phosphate termini.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/non-homologous-end-joining] Little is known about the function of nucleases in NHEJ.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/non-homologous-end-joining] Artemis is required for opening the hairpins that are formed on DNA ends during V(D)J recombination, a specific type of NHEJ, and may also participate in end trimming during general NHEJ.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/non-homologous-end-joining] Mre11 has nuclease activity, but it seems to be involved in homologous recombination, not NHEJ.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/non-homologous-end-joining] The X family DNA polymerases Pol λ and Pol μ (Pol4 in yeast) fill gaps during NHEJ.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/non-homologous-end-joining] Yeast lacking Pol4 are unable to join 3' overhangs that require gap filling, but remain proficient for gap filling at 5' overhangs.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/non-homologous-end-joining] This is because the primer terminus used to initiate DNA synthesis is less stable at 3' overhangs, necessitating a specialized NHEJ polymerase.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/non-homologous-end-joining] The DNA ligase IV complex, consisting of the catalytic subunit DNA ligase IV and its cofactor XRCC4 (Dnl4 and Lif1 in yeast), performs the ligation step of repair.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/non-homologous-end-joining] XLF, also known as Cernunnos, is homologous to yeast Nej1 and is also required for NHEJ.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/non-homologous-end-joining] While the precise role of XLF is unknown, it interacts with the XRCC4/DNA ligase IV complex and likely participates in the ligation step.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/non-homologous-end-joining] Recent evidence suggests that XLF promotes re-adenylation of DNA ligase IV after ligation, recharging the ligase and allowing it to catalyze a second ligation.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/non-homologous-end-joining] In yeast, Sir2 was originally identified as an NHEJ protein, but is now known to be required for NHEJ only because it is required for the transcription of Nej1.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/non-homologous-end-joining] Induction of heat-labile sites (HLS) is a signature of ionizing radiation.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/non-homologous-end-joining] The DNA clustered damage sites consist of different types of DNA lesions.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/non-homologous-end-joining] Some of these lesions are not prompt DSBs but they convert to DSB after heating.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/non-homologous-end-joining] HLS are not evolved to DSB under physiological temperature (37 C).
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/non-homologous-end-joining] Also, the interaction of HLS with other lesions and their role in living cells is yet elusive.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/non-homologous-end-joining] The repair mechanisms of these sites are not fully revealed.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/non-homologous-end-joining] The NHEJ is the dominant DNA repair pathway throughout the cell cycle.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/non-homologous-end-joining] The DNA-PKcs protein is the critical element in the center of NHEJ.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/non-homologous-end-joining] Using DNA-PKcs KO cell lines or inhibition of DNA-PKcs does not affect the repair capacity of HLS.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/non-homologous-end-joining] Also blocking both HR and NHEJ repair pathways by dactolisib (NVP-BEZ235) inhibitor showed that repair of HLS is not dependent on HR and NHEJ.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/non-homologous-end-joining] The choice between NHEJ and homologous recombination for repair of a double-strand break is regulated at the initial step in recombination, 5' end resection.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/non-homologous-end-joining] In this step, the 5' strand of the break is degraded by nucleases to create long 3' single-stranded tails.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/non-homologous-end-joining] DSBs that have not been resected can be rejoined by NHEJ, but resection of even a few nucleotides strongly inhibits NHEJ and effectively commits the break to repair by recombination.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/non-homologous-end-joining] NHEJ is active throughout the cell cycle, but is most important during G1 when no homologous template for recombination is available.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/non-homologous-end-joining] This regulation is accomplished by the cyclin-dependent kinase Cdk1 (Cdc28 in yeast), which is turned off in G1 and expressed in S and G2.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/non-homologous-end-joining] Cdk1 phosphorylates the nuclease Sae2, allowing resection to initiate.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/non-homologous-end-joining] NHEJ plays a critical role in V(D)J recombination, the process by which B-cell and T-cell receptor diversity is generated in the vertebrate immune system.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/non-homologous-end-joining] In V(D)J recombination, hairpin-capped double-strand breaks are created by the RAG1/RAG2 nuclease, which cleaves the DNA at recombination signal sequences.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/non-homologous-end-joining] These hairpins are then opened by the Artemis nuclease and joined by NHEJ.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/non-homologous-end-joining] A specialized DNA polymerase called terminal deoxynucleotidyl transferase (TdT), which is only expressed in lymph tissue, adds nontemplated nucleotides to the ends before the break is joined.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/non-homologous-end-joining] This process couples "variable" (V), "diversity" (D), and "joining" (J) regions, which when assembled together create the variable region of a B-cell or T-cell receptor gene.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/non-homologous-end-joining] Unlike typical cellular NHEJ, in which accurate repair is the most favorable outcome, error-prone repair in V(D)J recombination is beneficial in that it maximizes diversity in the coding sequence of these genes.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/non-homologous-end-joining] Patients with mutations in NHEJ genes are unable to produce functional B cells and T cells and suffer from severe combined immunodeficiency (SCID).
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/non-homologous-end-joining] Telomeres are normally protected by a "cap" that prevents them from being recognized as double-strand breaks.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/non-homologous-end-joining] Loss of capping proteins causes telomere shortening and inappropriate joining by NHEJ, producing dicentric chromosomes which are then pulled apart during mitosis.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/non-homologous-end-joining] Paradoxically, some NHEJ proteins are involved in telomere capping.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/non-homologous-end-joining] For example, Ku localizes to telomeres and its deletion leads to shortened telomeres.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/non-homologous-end-joining] Ku is also required for subtelomeric silencing, the process by which genes located near telomeres are turned off.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/non-homologous-end-joining] Several human syndromes are associated with dysfunctional NHEJ.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/non-homologous-end-joining] Hypomorphic mutations in LIG4 and XLF cause LIG4 syndrome and XLF-SCID, respectively.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/non-homologous-end-joining] These syndromes share many features including cellular radiosensitivity, microcephaly and severe combined immunodeficiency (SCID) due to defective V(D)J recombination.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/non-homologous-end-joining] Loss-of-function mutations in Artemis also cause SCID, but these patients do not show the neurological defects associated with LIG4 or XLF mutations.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/non-homologous-end-joining] The difference in severity may be explained by the roles of the mutated proteins.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/non-homologous-end-joining] Artemis is a nuclease and is thought to be required only for repair of DSBs with damaged ends, whereas DNA Ligase IV and XLF are required for all NHEJ events.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/non-homologous-end-joining] Mutations in genes that participate in non-homologous end joining lead to ataxia-telangiectasia (ATM gene), Fanconi anemia (multiple genes), as well as hereditary breast and ovarian cancers (BRCA1 gene).
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/non-homologous-end-joining] Many NHEJ genes have been knocked out in mice.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/non-homologous-end-joining] Deletion of XRCC4 or LIG4 causes embryonic lethality in mice, indicating that NHEJ is essential for viability in mammals.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/non-homologous-end-joining] In contrast, mice lacking Ku or DNA-PKcs are viable, probably because low levels of end joining can still occur in the absence of these components.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/non-homologous-end-joining] All NHEJ mutant mice show a SCID phenotype, sensitivity to ionizing radiation, and neuronal apoptosis.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/non-homologous-end-joining] A system was developed for measuring NHEJ efficiency in the mouse.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/non-homologous-end-joining] NHEJ efficiency could be compared across tissues of the same mouse and in mice of different age.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/non-homologous-end-joining] Efficiency was higher in the skin, lung and kidney fibroblasts, and lower in heart fibroblasts and brain astrocytes.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/non-homologous-end-joining] Furthermore, NHEJ efficiency declined with age.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/non-homologous-end-joining] The decline was 1.8 to 3.8-fold, depending on the tissue, in the 5-month-old compared to the 24-month-old mice.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/non-homologous-end-joining] Reduced capability for NHEJ can lead to an increase in the number of unrepaired or faultily repaired DNA double-strand breaks that may then contribute to aging.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/non-homologous-end-joining] An analysis of the level of NHEJ protein Ku80 in human, cow, and mouse indicated that Ku80 levels vary dramatically between species, and that these levels are strongly correlated with species longevity.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/protospacer-adjacent-motif] A **protospacer adjacent motif** (**PAM**) is a 2–6-base pair DNA sequence immediately following the DNA sequence targeted by the Cas9 nuclease in the CRISPR bacterial adaptive immune system.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/protospacer-adjacent-motif] The PAM is a component of the invading virus or plasmid, but is not found in the bacterial host genome and hence is not a component of the bacterial CRISPR locus.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/protospacer-adjacent-motif] Cas9 will not successfully bind to or cleave the target DNA sequence if it is not followed by the PAM sequence.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/protospacer-adjacent-motif] PAM is an essential targeting component which distinguishes bacterial self from non-self DNA, thereby preventing the CRISPR locus from being targeted and destroyed by the CRISPR-associated nuclease.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/protospacer-adjacent-motif] In a bacterial genome, CRISPR loci contain "spacers" (viral DNA inserted into a CRISPR locus) that in type II adaptive immune systems were created from invading viral or plasmid DNA (called "protospacers").
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/protospacer-adjacent-motif] Upon subsequent invasion, a CRISPR-associated nuclease such as Cas9 attaches to a tracrRNA–crRNA complex, which guides Cas9 to the invading protospacer sequence.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/protospacer-adjacent-motif] But Cas9 will not cleave the protospacer sequence unless there is an adjacent PAM sequence.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/protospacer-adjacent-motif] The spacer in the bacterial CRISPR loci will not contain a PAM sequence, and thus will not be cut by the nuclease, but the protospacer in the invading virus or plasmid will contain the PAM sequence, and thus will be cleaved by the Cas9 nuclease.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/protospacer-adjacent-motif] The canonical Cas9 PAM is the sequence 5'-NGG-3', where "N" is any nucleobase followed by two guanine ("G") nucleobases. sgRNAs can transport Cas9 to any locus in the genome for gene editing, but no editing can occur at any site other than one at which Cas9 recognizes PAM.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/protospacer-adjacent-motif] The canonical PAM is associated with the Cas9 nuclease of *Streptococcus pyogenes* (designated SpCas9), whereas different PAMs are associated with the Cas9 proteins of the bacteria *Neisseria meningitidis*, *Treponema denticola*, and *Streptococcus thermophilus*.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/protospacer-adjacent-motif] 5'-NGA-3' can be a highly efficient non-canonical PAM for human cells, but efficiency varies with genome location.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/protospacer-adjacent-motif] Attempts have been made to engineer Cas9s to recognize different PAMs in order to improve the ability of CRISPR-Cas9 to edit genes at any desired genome location.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/protospacer-adjacent-motif] The Cas9 of *Francisella novicida* recognizes the canonical PAM sequence 5'-NGG-3', but has been engineered to recognize 5'-YG-3' (where "Y" is a pyrimidine), thus adding to the range of possible Cas9 targets.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/protospacer-adjacent-motif] The Cpf1 nuclease of *Francisella novicida* recognizes the PAM 5'-TTTN-3' or 5'-YTN-3'.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/protospacer-adjacent-motif] Aside from CRISPR-Cas9 and CRISPR-Cpf1, there are doubtless many yet undiscovered nucleases and PAMs.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/protospacer-adjacent-motif] CRISPR/Cas13a (formerly C2c2) from the bacterium *Leptotrichia shahii* is an RNA-guided CRISPR system that targets sequences in RNA rather than DNA.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/protospacer-adjacent-motif] PAM is not relevant for an RNA-targeting CRISPR, although a guanine flanking the target negatively affects efficacy, and has been designated a "protospacer flanking site" (PFS).
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/protospacer-adjacent-motif] A technology called GUIDE-Seq has been devised to assay off-target cleavages produced by such gene editing.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/protospacer-adjacent-motif] The PAM requirement can be exploited to specifically target single-nucleotide heterozygous mutations while exerting no aberrant effects on wild-type alleles.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/tracrrna] In molecular biology, **trans-activating CRISPR RNA** (**tracrRNA**) is a small *trans*-encoded RNA.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/tracrrna] First, a copy of the invading nucleic acid is integrated into the CRISPR locus.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/tracrrna] Next, CRISPR RNAs (crRNAs) are transcribed from this CRISPR locus.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/tracrrna] The crRNAs are then incorporated into effector complexes, where the crRNA guides the complex to the invading nucleic acid and the Cas proteins degrade this nucleic acid.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/tracrrna] There are several CRISPR system subtypes.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/tracrrna] Type II CRISPR-Cas systems require a tracrRNA which plays a role in the maturation of crRNA.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/tracrrna] The tracrRNA is partially complementary to and base pairs with a pre-crRNA forming an RNA duplex.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/tracrrna] This is cleaved by RNase III, an RNA-specific ribonuclease, to form a crRNA/tracrRNA hybrid.
[src:crispr-cas9-deep/tracrrna] This hybrid acts as a guide for the endonuclease Cas9, which cleaves the invading nucleic acid.
